                            <comment id="14476149" author="stevedonie" created="Tue, 24 Jun 2014 10:24:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Did some debugging on this and the problem appears to be having &quot;-n&quot; somewhere in the path to the script. In startGroovy.bat, there is this code:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;rem horrible roll your own arg processing inspired by jruby equivalent

rem escape minus (-d), quotes (-q), star (-s).
set _ARGS=%*
if not defined _ARGS goto execute
set _ARGS=%_ARGS:-=-d%
set _ARGS=%_ARGS:&quot;=-q%
set _ARGS=%_ARGS:?=-n%
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;and then later on there is this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;rem now unescape -q, -s, -d
set _ARG=%_ARG:-s=*%
set _ARG=%_ARG:-q=&quot;%
set _ARG=%_ARG:-d=-%
set _ARG=%_ARG:-n=?%
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I think the problem would also be exposed by having a script named &quot;anything-s.groovy&quot; &quot;anything-d.groovy&quot; or &quot;anything-q.groovy&quot; or &quot;anything-n.groovy&quot;. I also experienced the problem when I passed a fully qualified path to a script that had a &quot;-n&quot; in it, like this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;groovy.bat c:\test-new\script.groovy
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;



</comment>
                            <comment id="14476302" author="fintelia" created="Tue, 22 Jul 2014 12:43:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Those are the relevant lines of code, though you did not describe exactly what is going wrong. The very first replacement changes all dashes into &quot;-d&quot; to prevent them from interfering with any of the other conversions. The second block then converts instances of &quot;-d&quot; back into dashes:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&quot;anything-s.groovy&quot; -&amp;gt; &quot;anything-ds.groovy&quot; -&amp;gt; &quot;anything-s.groovy&quot;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The issue is that &quot;-n&quot; is converted into a question mark &lt;em&gt;after&lt;/em&gt; the &quot;-d&quot; to dash replacement:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&quot;anything-n.groovy&quot; -&amp;gt; &quot;anything-dn.groovy&quot; -&amp;gt; &quot;anything-n.groovy&quot; -&amp;gt; &quot;anything?.groovy&quot;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is simply a matter of swapping those last two lines. I have submitted a &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/groovy/groovy-core/pull/490/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;pull request&lt;/a&gt; that does just that.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14480658" author="paulk" created="Wed, 23 Jul 2014 02:54:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for raising the issue. It should be fixed in the next release. And thanks to Jonathan for the PR.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
